revision.text:
{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}} '''ATryn''' is the brand name of the [[anticoagulant]] [[antithrombin]] manufactured by the [[Massachusetts]]-based U.S. company [[rEVO Biologics]] (formerly known as GTC Biotherapeutics). It is made from the milk of goats that have been [[Genetic engineering|genetically modified]] to produce human antithrombin, a [[Blood proteins|plasma protein]] with anticoagulant properties.<ref name="Reuters">{{cite news | title = U.S. approves first drug from DNA-altered animals | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE5154OE20090206 | first = Susan | last = Heavey | date = February 6, 2009 | accessdate = February 7, 2009 |agency=Reuters | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090209111233/https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE5154OE20090206| archivedate= February 9, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> [[Microinjection]] was used to insert human antithrombin genes into the [[cell nucleus]] of their [[embryo]]s.<ref name="Jones">{{cite web | first= Phillip B. C | last = Jones | title=European Regulators Curdle Plans for Goat Milk Human Antithrombin | url = http://www.isb.vt.edu/articles/apr0603.htm | date = April 2006 | accessdate= February 7, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090211105703/http://www.isb.vt.edu/articles/apr0603.htm| archivedate= February 11, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> ATryn is the first medicine produced using genetically engineered animals.<ref name="Bloomberg">{{cite news | title = GTC Drug Is First From Genetically Engineered Animals | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aqXXW3MCHV5Q&refer=us | publisher = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | first = Catherine | last = Larkin | date = February 6, 2009 | accessdate = February 7, 2009 }}</ref> GTC states that one genetically modified goat can produce the same amount of antithrombin in a year as 90,000 blood donations.<ref name="HT">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20090207/ZNYT04/902073008/-1/LIVING01?Title=F_D_A__Approves_Drug_From_Gene_Altered_Goats|title=F.D.A. Approves Drug From Gene-Altered Goats|last=Pollack|first=Andrew| accessdate = February 7, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090211095432/http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20090207/ZNYT04/902073008/-1/LIVING01?Title=F_D_A__Approves_Drug_From_Gene_Altered_Goats| archivedate= February 11, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> GTC chose goats for the process because they reproduce more rapidly than cattle and produce more protein than rabbits or mice.<ref>{{cite news | title = The Land of Milk and Money | url = http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?id=atryn-the-land-of-milk-and-mone&page=2 | date = January 15, 2009 | accessdate = February 11, 2009 |work=[[Scientific American]] | first = Gary | last = Stix }}</ref>
On February 6, 2009, ATryn was approved by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) for treatment of patients with hereditary [[Antithrombin III deficiency|antithrombin deficiency]] who are undergoing surgical or childbirth procedures.<ref name="Reuters"/> Along with the approval from the FDA's pharmaceutical regulatory board, the [[Center for Veterinary Medicine]] of the FDA also approved the genetic makeup of the goats that are used to manufacture ATryn.<ref name="Bloomberg"/> rEVO has the sole rights to sell ATryn in the United States,<ref name="Bloomberg"/> and the drug is available in the U.S. market.<ref name="Reuters"/> Earlier in 2006, the [[European Medicines Agency]] (EMA) initially rejected and, after an appeal from GTC, approved the drug for use in the [[European Union]] countries.<ref name="Jones"/><ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/5041298.stm |title= Go-ahead for 'pharmed' goat drug |date = June 2, 2006 | accessdate= February 7, 2009 |publisher=BBC | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070121074401/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/5041298.stm| archivedate=January 21, 2007<!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = ATryn, on Old MacDonald's Pharm | url = http://www.sciam.com/blog/60-second-science/post.cfm?id=dont-have-a-cow-but-fda-could-appro-2009-01-09 | date = September 2006 | accessdate = February 7, 2009 |work=[[Scientific American]] | first = Charles | last = Choi | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090211064625/http://www.sciam.com/blog/60-second-science/post.cfm?id=dont-have-a-cow-but-fda-could-appro-2009-01-09| archivedate= February 11, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
According to Tom Newberry, the spokesperson for GTC, the company plans to acquire additional approval for treatment of those with non-hereditary antithrombin deficiency.<ref name="Bloomberg"/>
The [[Humane Society of the United States]] has said of the process used to manufacture ATryn, "It is a mechanistic use of animals that seems to perpetuate the notion of their being merely tools for human use rather than sentient creatures."<ref name="HT"/><ref>{{cite web|title=HSUS Position Statement: Genetic Engineering of Animals |url=http://www.hsus.org/animals_in_research/general_information_on_animal_research/hsus_position_statements/hsus_position_statement__genetic_engineering_of_animals.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203040734/http://www.hsus.org/animals_in_research/general_information_on_animal_research/hsus_position_statements/hsus_position_statement__genetic_engineering_of_animals.html |archivedate=December 3, 2008 }}</ref> However, the genetic change has no known ill-effects on the host animal.{{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}
