In [[civil engineering]], '''machine control''' is used to accurately position [[Earthworks (engineering)|earthwork]] machinery based on 3D design models and [[GPS in the Earthmoving Industry|GPS systems]], and thus aid machine operators to e.g. control the position of a road [[grader]]'s blade.<ref name="heikkila">{{citation |last1=Heikkilä |first1=Rauno |last2=Jaakkola |first2=Mika |year=2003 |title=Intelligent Road Construction Site - Development of Automation into total Working Process of Finnish Road Construction |journal=2003 Proceedings of the 20th ISARC |place=Eindhoven, Holland |url=http://www.iaarc.org/publications/fulltext/isarc2003-61.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref> Many machine control systems utilize the [[Real Time Kinematic|Real Time Kinematic (RTK) system]] to improve the positioning accuracy.
There are four dominant manufacturers of machine control systems: [http://moba-automation.com/ MOBA Mobile Automation AG], [[Trimble Navigation]] Limited, [[Topcon]] Positioning Systems and [[Leica Geosystems]]. In 2010, The Kellogg Report<ref>The Kellogg Report LLC (2010). Article: The Kellogg Report. Retrieved December 15, 2010 from http://www.kelloggreport.com/index.html{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> was published to serve as a resource for comparing the systems from these and other manufacturers.
